{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17648717","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17648717"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T20:56:50+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T20:56:50+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18327"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18327","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18327"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.05,0.86,0,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11045"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79189"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11045","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11045"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18327"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64541"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25627"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25631"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79189","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/79189"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 68-year-old woman presents to the Orthopaedic clinic with chronic knee pain and instability. She has a history of multiple failed knee arthroplasties, with the most recent surgery complicated by a deep infection. Despite extensive antibiotic therapy, the infection persists. She has significant bone loss around the knee joint, and her mobility is severely limited. She is unable to weightbear on the affected leg and uses a wheelchair for mobility.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate indication for knee arthrodesis in this patient?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Chronic knee pain with intact joint surfaces","Recurrent knee dislocation without infection","Persistent deep infection after multiple knee arthroplasties","Mild osteoarthritis with occasional pain","Stable knee joint with mild ligamentous laxity"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPersistent deep infection after multiple knee arthroplasties\u003C/strong\u003E is a clear indication for knee arthrodesis. In cases where infection cannot be eradicated and there is significant bone loss, arthrodesis provides a stable, pain-free limb, albeit at the cost of joint mobility.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChronic knee pain with intact joint surfaces\u003C/strong\u003E would not warrant arthrodesis, as other less invasive treatments could be considered.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERecurrent knee dislocation without infection\u003C/strong\u003E might be managed with ligament reconstruction or other stabilising procedures rather than arthrodesis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMild osteoarthritis with occasional pain\u003C/strong\u003E is usually managed conservatively or with joint-preserving surgeries, not arthrodesis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStable knee joint with mild ligamentous laxity\u003C/strong\u003E would not require arthrodesis, as this condition can often be managed with physical therapy or bracing.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Knee arthrodesis is indicated in cases of severe joint instability or infection where other surgical options are not viable.","It is also considered when there is a failure of total knee arthroplasty with significant bone loss or infection.","Arthrodesis provides pain relief and stability but sacrifices joint mobility."],"references":["Khurana, I., Khurana, A., \u0026 Kowlgi, N. G. (2019). Textbook of Medical Physiology_-E-book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Datta HK, Ng WF, Walker JA, Tuck SP, Varanasi SS. The cell biology of bone metabolism. J Clin Pathol. 2008 May;61(5):577-87. doi: 10.1136/jcp.2007.048868. PMID: 18441154","Patton, K. T., \u0026 Thibodeau, G. A. (2018). Anthony\u0027s Textbook of Anatomy \u0026 Physiology-E-Book: Anthony\u0027s Textbook of Anatomy \u0026 Physiology-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Smith, R., \u0026 Wordsworth, P. (2016). Oxford textbook of clinical and biochemical disorders of the skeleton. Oxford University Press"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64541"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18327"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64541","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/64541"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-13T16:46:37+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-13T16:47:16+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11045"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79189"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"34","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/34"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddb4","name":"Orthopaedics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self"